### Culture

The culture of England is often difficult to distinguish from the [culture of the United Kingdom](/Culture_of_the_United_Kingdom), given its significant influence on the cultures of the British Isles and, conversely, the influence of other cultures on life in England.

#### Religion

The [established religion](/Established_church) of England is the [Church of England](/Church_of_England), with [Charles III](/Charles_III) as its titular head. The worldwide [Anglican Communion](/Anglican_Communion) is overseen by the [General Synod](/General_Synod). Twenty-six of the church's 42 bishops serve as [Lords Spiritual](/Lords_Spiritual) in the [House of Lords](/House_of_Lords). In 2010, the Church of England reported 25 million baptised members out of approximately 41 million Christians in Great Britain. Around this time, it also claimed to baptise one in eight newborn children. Generally, any resident in England can marry or be buried in their local [parish church](/Church_of_England), irrespective of their baptismal status. Regular attendance has declined since 1890, with about one million (10% of the baptised population) attending Sunday services monthly and roughly three million (15%) attending Christmas services.

[Saint George](/Saint_George) is recognized as the [patron saint](/Patron_saint) of England, and his cross forms the [flag of England](/Flag_of_England). Prior to [Edward III](/Edward_III_of_England), [St Edmund](/Edmund_the_Martyr) was the patron saint, and [Saint Alban](/Saint_Alban) is also honored as England's [first martyr](/Protomartyr).

A survey conducted in late 2008 found that 47.0% of the population of England and Wales were affiliated with the [Church of England](/Church_of_England), which is also the [state church](/State_church). Other affiliations included 9.6% with the [Roman Catholic Church](/Roman_Catholicism_in_England), 8.7% with other Christian denominations (primarily [Free church](/Free_church) [Protestants](/Protestantism) and [Eastern Orthodox Christians](/Eastern_Orthodox_Christians)), 4.8% Muslim, 3.4% from other religions, 5.3% agnostic, 6.8% atheist, and 15.0% unsure or unwilling to answer.

Religious observances of [St George's Day](/St_George%27s_Day) (April 23) may be shifted if it falls too close to [Easter](/Easter). According to the [Church of England](/Church_of_England)'s calendar, if St George's Day occurs between [Palm Sunday](/Palm_Sunday) and the Second Sunday of Easter, it is observed on the Monday following the Second Sunday of Easter.

#### Language

English people traditionally speak the [English language](/English_language), a member of the [West Germanic](/West_Germanic_languages) [language family](/Language_family). Modern English evolved from [Middle English](/Middle_English_language), which was influenced by Norman-French, [Old French](/Old_French), and [Latin](/Latin). During the Middle English period, Latin was the language of administration, and Norman French was spoken by the nobility. Middle English itself derived from the [Old English](/Old_English_language) of the Anglo-Saxon era, with the [Old Norse](/Old_Norse) language of Danish settlers also influencing the language in northern and eastern England.

Historically, England had numerous distinct dialects of modern English, documented in projects like the [English Dialect Dictionary](/English_Dialect_Dictionary) and the [Survey of English Dialects](/Survey_of_English_Dialects). However, widespread [dialect levelling](/Dialect_levelling) has occurred more recently due to factors like education, media influence, and socio-economic pressures.

[Cornish](/Cornish_language), a [Celtic language](/Celtic_languages), is one of three extant Brittonic languages and has seen a revival in [Cornwall](/Cornwall). Historically, [Cumbric](/Cumbric_language), another Brittonic Celtic language, was spoken in [Cumbria](/Cumbria) in [North West England](/North_West_England) but died out by the 11th century, though traces remain in the Cumbrian dialect. [Early Modern English](/Early_Modern_English) emerged in the late 15th century with the introduction of the [printing press](/Printing_press) to London and the [Great Vowel Shift](/Great_Vowel_Shift). Through the global influence of the [British Empire](/British_Empire), English spread worldwide from the 17th to the mid-20th centuries. Modern English has become the [international language](/International_auxiliary_language) of [business](/Business), [science](/Science), [communication](/Communication), [sports](/Sports), [aviation](/Aviation), and [diplomacy](/Diplomacy), facilitated by various media and the rise of the United States as a global power.

#### Literature

English literature originates with [Anglo-Saxon literature](/Anglo-Saxon_literature), written in [Old English](/Old_English), which produced epic works like [Beowulf](/Beowulf) and fragments such as [The Battle of Maldon](/The_Battle_of_Maldon), [The Seafarer](/The_Seafarer_(poem)), and [The Wanderer](/The_Wanderer_(Old_English_poem)). For a considerable period, [Latin](/Latin) and [French](/French_language) were the dominant literary languages in England. However, the [medieval period](/Medieval_period) saw a flourishing of literature in [Middle English](/Middle_English), with [Geoffrey Chaucer](/Geoffrey_Chaucer) being its most renowned writer.

The [Elizabethan era](/Elizabethan_era) is often regarded as a golden age of English literature, featuring prominent writers such as [William Shakespeare](/William_Shakespeare), [Thomas Nashe](/Thomas_Nashe), [Edmund Spenser](/Edmund_Spenser), [Sir Philip Sidney](/Sir_Philip_Sidney), [Christopher Marlowe](/Christopher_Marlowe), and [Ben Jonson](/Ben_Jonson).

Other notable English authors include [Jane Austen](/Jane_Austen), [Arnold Bennett](/Arnold_Bennett), [Rupert Brooke](/Rupert_Brooke), [Agatha Christie](/Agatha_Christie), [Charles Dickens](/Charles_Dickens), [Thomas Hardy](/Thomas_Hardy), [A. E. Housman](/A._E._Housman), [George Orwell](/George_Orwell), and the [Lake Poets](/Lake_Poets).

In a 2003 [BBC](/BBC) survey titled [The Big Read](/The_Big_Read), aimed at identifying the "nation's best-loved novel," works by English novelists such as [J. R. R. Tolkien](/J._R._R._Tolkien), [Jane Austen](/Jane_Austen), [Philip Pullman](/Philip_Pullman), [Douglas Adams](/Douglas_Adams), and [J. K. Rowling](/J._K._Rowling) secured the top five positions.

